Pickett and Wilkinson (2009): The Spirit Level: Why Equality is Better for Everyone

Motivation

  • Are social malaises caused/associated with higher levels of inequality?
    • Causation vs.Â correlation.
    • What is inequality? Relative measure within a country. It is not absolute or a welfare measure across countries.
  • We will analyse a set of social illnesses and how inequality could cause them.
    • Evolutionary psychology arguments.
    • Higher inequality leads to a greater emphasis in social status, higher stress derived from the need to keep oneâs position in the social hierarchy and a more materialistic society in general.

Q5: Wilkinson and Pickett (2009) state that: âthe fact that so many relationships with inequality are statistically significant, despite the limits to the data, is an indication of how powerful the underlying relationships actually are.â Using what you know about simple regression and hypothesis testing, discuss Wilkinson and Pickettâs statement.

Q5: Wilkinson and Pickett (2009) state that: âthe fact that so many relationships with inequality are statistically significant, despite the limits to the data, is an indication of how powerful the underlying relationships actually are.â Using what you know about simple regression and hypothesis testing, discuss Wilkinson and Pickettâs statement.

  • Could the true value of the relationship be zero? True fixed unknown parameter belongs to the confidence interval.
  • What are the determinants of the confidence interval? Point estimate, standard errors, and the critical value for a given size.
  • If the estimator is unbiased, the point estimate cannot be improved.

Q5: Wilkinson and Pickett (2009) state that: âthe fact that so many relationships with inequality are statistically significant, despite the limits to the data, is an indication of how powerful the underlying relationships actually are.â Using what you know about simple regression and hypothesis testing, discuss Wilkinson and Pickettâs statement.

  • The lower the number of observations implies that the critical value \(c\) will be relatively large.
  • The standard error becomes lower as the number of observations increases.
  • WP even though we have this challenging setup, the relationships are indeed statistically significant.
